# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bacillati
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bacillati/acidimicrobiia] The ***Acidimicrobiia*** are a class of Actinomycetota, in which three families, eight genera, and nine species have been described, *Acidimicrobium ferrooxidans* is the type species of the order.
[src:bacillati/acidimicrobiia] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature (LPSN) and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriia] The "**Acidobacteriia**" is a class of Acidobacteriota.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriia] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriia] Numbered orders do not yet have any cultured representatives.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] Members of this phylum are physiologically diverse, and can be found in a variety of environments including soil, decomposing wood, hot springs, oceans, caves, and metal-contaminated soils.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] The members of this phylum are particularly abundant in soil habitats representing up to 52% of the total bacterial community.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] Environmental factors such as pH and nutrients have been seen to drive Acidobacteriota dynamics.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] Many Acidobacteriota are acidophilic, including the first described member of the phylum, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] There is much that is unknown about Acidobacteria both in their form and function.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] Thus, this is a growing field of microbiology.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] Some of this uncertainty can be attributed to the difficulty with which these bacteria are grown in the laboratory.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] There has been recent success in propagation by using low concentrations of nutrients in combination with high amounts of CO2, yet, progress is still quite slow.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] These new methods have only allowed approximately 30% of subdivisions to have species documented.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] Additionally, many of the samples sequenced do not have taxonomic names as they have not yet been fully characterized.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] This area of study is a very current topic, and scientific understanding is expected to grow and change as new information comes to light.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] Other notable species are *Holophaga foetida*, *Geothrix fermentans*, *Acanthopleuribacter pedis* and *Bryobacter aggregatus*.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] Since they have only recently been discovered and the large majority have not been cultured, the ecology and metabolism of these bacteria is not well understood.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] However, these bacteria may be an important contributor to ecosystems, since they are particularly abundant within soils.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivisions 1, 4, and 6 are found to be particularly abundant in soils.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] As well as their natural soil habitat, unclassified subdivision 2 Acidobacteriota have also been identified as a contaminant of DNA extraction kit reagents, which may lead to their erroneous appearance in microbiota or metagenomic datasets.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 1 have been found to dominate in low pH conditions.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] Additionally, Acidobacteriota from acid mine drainage have been found to be more adapted to acidic pH conditions (pH 2–3) compared to Acidobacteriota from soils, potentially due to cell specialization and enzyme stability.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] The G+C content of Acidobacteria genomes are consistent within their subdivisions - above 60% for group V fragments and roughly 10% lower for group III fragments.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] The majority of Acidobacteriota are considered aerobes.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] There are some Acidobacteriota that are considered anaerobes within subdivision 8 and subdivision 23.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] It has been found that some strains of Acidobacteriota originating from soils have the genomic potential to respire oxygen at atmospheric and sub-atmospheric concentrations.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] Members of the *Acidobacteriota* phylum have been considered oligotrophic bacteria due to high abundances in low organic carbon environments.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] However, the variation in this phylum may indicate that they may not have the same ecological strategy.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] The first species, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*, of this phylum was discovered in 1991.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] However, Acidobacteriota were not recognized as a distinct clade until 1997, and were not recognized as a phylum until 2012.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] In an effort to further classify Acidobacteria, 16S rRNA gene regions were sequenced from many different strains.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] These sequences lead to the formation of subdivisions within the phyla.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] Today, there are 26 accepted subdivisions recognized in the Ribosomal Database Project.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] Much of this variety comes from populations of acidobacteria found in soils contaminated with uranium.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] Therefore, most of the known species in this phyla are concentrated in a few of the subdivisions, the largest being #1.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] Most of these microbes are aerobes, and they are all heterotrophic.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] Subdivision 1 contains 11 of the known genera in addition to the majority of the species that have been able to be cultivated thus far.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] Within the 22 known genera, there are 40 conclusive species.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] The genera are divided amongst subdivisions 3, 4, 8, 10, 23, and 1.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] As the Acidobateria are a developing area of microbiology, it is hypothesized that these numbers will change drastically with further study.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] Some members of subdivision 1 are able to use D-glucose, D-xylose, and lactose as carbon sources, but are unable to use fucose or sorbose.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 1 also contain enzymes such as galactosidases used in the breakdown of sugars.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 4 have been found to use chitin as a carbon source.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] Despite the presence of genetic information generally known to encode for carbohydrate processing machinery in various genera of Acidobacteria, several experimental studies have demonstrated the inability to break down various polysaccharides.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] Cellulose is the main component of plant cell walls and a seemingly opportune resource for carbon.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] However, only a single species across all subdivisions has been shown to process it, *Telmactobacter bradus* from subvision 1.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] Researchers believe that an additional factor in the lack of understanding of carbon degradation by acidobacteria may stem from the present limited ability to provide adequate cultivation conditions.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] To study the natural behavior of these bacteria, they must grow and live in a controlled, observable environment.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] If such a habitat cannot be provided, recorded data cannot reliably report on the activity of the microbes in question.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] Therefore, the inconsistencies between genome sequence based predictions and observed carbon processes may be explained by present study methods.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] There has been no clear evidence that Acidobacteriota are involved in nitrogen-cycle processes such as nitrification, denitrification, or nitrogen fixation.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] However, *Geothrix fermantans* was shown to be able to reduce nitrate and contained the norB gene.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] The NorB gene was also identified in *Koribacter verstailis* and *Solibacter usitatus*.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] In addition, the presence of the nirA gene has been observed in members of subdivision 1.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] Additionally, to date, all genomes have been described to directly uptake ammonium via ammonium channel transporter family genes.
[src:bacillati/acidobacteriota] Acidobacteriota can use both inorganic and organic nitrogen as their nitrogen sources.
[src:bacillati/acidulidesulfobacteriota] Acidulidesulfobacteriota are ecologically significant in biogeochemical cycling, especially with respect to sulfur and iron.
[src:bacillati/acidulidesulfobacteriota] Their genomes show evidence of interaction with viruses, which can influence host metabolic functions including folate biosynthesis and sulfur pathways.
[src:bacillati/actinomyces-israelii] Actinomycosis is most frequently caused by *A. israelii*.
[src:bacillati/actinomyces-israelii] It is a normal colonizer of the vagina, colon, and mouth.
[src:bacillati/actinomyces-israelii] Infection is established first by a breach of the mucosal barrier during various procedures (dental, gastrointestinal), aspiration, or pathologies such as diverticulitis.
[src:bacillati/actinomyces-israelii] The chronic phase of this disease is also known as the "classic phase" because the acute, early phase is often missed by health care providers.
[src:bacillati/actinomyces-israelii] This is characterized by slow, contiguous growth that ignores tissue planes and forms a sinus tract that can spontaneously heal and recur, leading to a densely fibrotic lesion.
[src:bacillati/actinomyces-israelii] This lesion is often characterized as "wooden".
[src:bacillati/actinomyces-israelii] Sulfur granules form in a central purulence surrounded by neutrophils.
[src:bacillati/bacillati] It derives its name (*terra* = "land") from the evolutionary pressures of life on land.
[src:bacillati/bacillati] Bacillati possess important adaptations such as resistance to environmental hazards (e.g., desiccation, ultraviolet radiation, and high salinity) and oxygenic photosynthesis.
[src:bacillati/bacillati] Also, the unique properties of the cell wall in gram-positive taxa, which likely evolved in response to terrestrial conditions, have contributed toward pathogenicity in many species.
[src:bacillati/bacillati] These results now leave open the possibility that terrestrial adaptations may have played a larger role in prokaryote evolution than currently understood.
[src:bacillati/bacillati] Bacillati) was proposed in 2004 for Actinomycetota, Cyanobacteria, and Deinococcota and was expanded later to include Bacillota and Chloroflexota.
[src:bacillati/bacillati] Other phylogenetic analyses have supported the close relationships of these phyla.
[src:bacillati/bacillati] Most species of prokaryotes not placed in "Terrabacteria" were assigned to the taxon "Hydrobacteria", (which is also known as kingdom Pseudomonadati) in reference to the moist environment inferred for the common ancestor of those species.
[src:bacillati/bacillati] Some molecular phylogenetic analyses have not supported this dichotomy of Bacillati and Pseudomonadati, but the most recent genomic analyses, including those that have focused on rooting the tree, have found these two groups to be monophyletic.
[src:bacillati/bacillati] Bacillati and Pseudomonadati were inferred to have diverged approximately 3 billion years ago, suggesting that land (continents) had been colonized by prokaryotes at that time.
[src:bacillati/bacillati] Together, Bacillati and Pseudomonadati form a large clade containing 97% of prokaryotes and 99% of all species of Bacteria known by 2009, and placed in the taxon "Selabacteria", in allusion to their phototrophic abilities (σέλας "light" in Greek).
[src:bacillati/bacillati] Currently, the bacterial phyla that are outside of Bacillati + Pseudomonadati, and thus justifying the taxon "Selabacteria", are debated and may or may not include Fusobacteria.
[src:bacillati/bacillati] The name “Glidobacteria” included some members of Bacillati but excluded the large gram positive groups, Bacillota and Actinomycetota, and is not supported by molecular phylogenetic data.
[src:bacillati/bacillati] Moreover, the article naming Glidobacteria did not include a molecular phylogeny or statistical analyses and did not follow the widely used three-domain system.
[src:bacillati/bacillati] For example, it claimed that eukaryotes split from Archaea very recently (~900 Mya), which is contradicted by the fossil record, and that lineage of eukaryotes + Archaea was nested within Bacteria as a close relative of Actinomycetota.
[src:bacillati/bacillati] In 2022, new rules were introduced for kingdom-level taxa of prokaryotes, and the same two authors who proposed those new rules, proposed new names in 2024.
[src:bacillati/bacillati] They concluded that “the taxonomically preferable solution for bacterial kingdoms seems to be to accept the subdivision apparent in the study by Battistuzzi and Hedges,” with refinement.
[src:bacillati/bacillati] The new (and only valid) name is kingdom Bacillati.
[src:bacillati/bacillati] The phylogenetic tree according to the phylogenetic analyses of Battistuzzi and Hedges (2009) is the following and with a molecular clock calibration.
[src:bacillati/bacillati] Recent molecular analyses have found roughly the following relationships including other phyla, whose relationships were uncertain.
[src:bacillati/bacillati] On the other hand, Coleman et al. named the clade composed of Thermotogota, Deinococcota, Synergistota and related as DST and furthermore the analysis suggests that ultra-small bacteria (CPR group) may belong to Bacillati being more closely related to Chloroflexota.
[src:bacillati/bacillati] According to this study the phylum Aquificota sometimes included belongs to Pseudomonadati and that the phylum Fusobacteriota can belong to both Bacillati and Pseudomonadati.
